If your pre-amp has an out, it may have a "direct monitor" feature which would allow you to hear. Otherwise I think you would need to go into your OS sound settings and "Listen to this device" to make the sound come out of your speakers, or headphones.

Also, record as quietly as you can; you can always raise volume but you can't really bring it back down. It'll take some experimentation to get it right, but it should be a kinda one-time thing (or at least something you can remember for the next time).

My friend, ASIAN GORL, dresses up like a black woman when she wants to seem sexy. She puts on flannel jackets, smoky t-shirts, and skin tight jeans. When asked, "ASIAN GORL, why do you have such quippy fashion sense?" she replies, "it is nippy outside, and I must warm the peoples. the people dem must know the sun."

I thought that was interesting. Did you know "sun," and "sonne," have the same meaning in German? That's also something I thought was interesting. Gutsybird sometimes posts about the ASIAN GORL meme too, but he doesn't really think her fashion sense is all to vain and provoked.

posts.name: seuss
posts.com:
Have you tried to bully a wave? Punch at it? Stupid! Did you know human beings spend most of their lives doing something different? Every minute of every day a human being (organism) is doing something different. They are never doing the same thing twice. There is always some idiosyncrasy to a repetition. The few people who complete the same task over and over again are called students, and the even fewer people who have mastered the art of repetition are called teachers. If seuss had to guess, there is about a one in a million chance that this time you and I have posted on [s4s] together is exactly the same as the last one.

The reason people love minutiae of differences is kind of cathartic. Like a religious reason. Imagine the world is made up of atoms and small little dots, and every time you do something, those dots rearrange in a specific way. The Japanese call it... Kintsugi. Restoration and replication is a kind of ideology, it doesn't excuse interpretation or nuance.

>Have you ever tried to bully a wave? Punch it? Kick it? Pinch it? Hit it? Beat it to death with a stick? Stupid. —Ruth Ozeki, A Tale for the Time Being

posts.name: seuss
posts.com:
The ASIAN GORL likes to drink coffee, but she also likes to drink it from a can. The Japanese do this a lot. I've read about this before. A can is opened and enjoyed from a mini-mart. Sometimes in the coldest weather a woman may wear a scarf, and drink these cans to excess. The trick is to enable just enough coffee to pass through the barrier between your high and your thirst, so as to seem unaffected. This of course means buying the right coffee can, with the precise amount of caffeine milligrams. Then once this holy marriage of human intoxication is bridged between oral opinion, you can throw the can away in a dumpster or recycle bin, depending on your hygiene habits and other preferences.

posts.name: seuss
posts.com:
Sometimes when I am with the ASIAN GORL just hanging out of course, I wonder who her boyfriend is. Even though she never brings him to our get-togethers, and there is a clear line between how she views ANTI-SEUSS as a person (diametrically to me of course), I can't help but wonder who this masked man is. Maybe Zorro could shed some light on the history of caped boyfriends, although I think a small designer cowl made from cow skin might seem a little garish and unfitting for describing ASIAN GORL's mystery man. There are times when we are at the mall, or in Macy's, thinking, "what if people get the wrong idea about us," and there's always that moment of infidelity where one person assumes the worst possible thing, that relationships "can exist without sex," and so the intimacy is convened on almost instinctively, without either having so much as kissed before.

posts.name: seuss
posts.com:
>In my sister’s story, / God can’t find us in any of / His coat pockets, / not in the empty, and not in the filled. / We’re in none of His hands, the kind or the terrible; / none of His shoes, the giant or the minute. / And neither are we hiding inside the apples, / neither in the perfect nor the ruined. / Not in the first mouthful, and not in the last. —Li-Young Lee, The Shortcut Home

Are you a romantic? Do you think about love under a lamp-lit dinner? Or maybe a skyline filled with lights, during a dusky summer's evening. Is love something you consider only when mystery is involved? And if there is a mystery, are you emotionally attached to that rapacious feeling of excitement that unravels it? These are a lot of questions. Osamu Dazai asked a lot of questions too. He did ask a bunch of questions about the meaning of life and the state of it between invalids in his literature. Romance especially. ASIAN GORL should be as good as any a muse to bridge the gap between a romantic interest and a meaningful love life. Sometimes, love is standing there, staring us in the face. Bold and obvious as the sun which rises with it, but we are too blind to commercialized romance to see its charms. Too busy with the everyday schizophrenia of media to believe in bareness. Imagine if ASIAN GORL were just that, made for you and you for her, without any comeuppance, mystery or deprivation of imagination. Just that. Your lover.

posts.name: seuss

>The Japanese language is nothing but lies. Or maybe just chaos. "What happens twice will happen again." OK, I buy that. But how can that idea coexist with "Third time's the charm?" Farewell, mother tongue. —Hideo Furukawa, Slow Boat

Did you ever throw a die? Roll a hard six? Snake eyes? Midnight? Did you feel lucky when your hands proved impervious to circumstance? Nothing surrounding you can injure that feeling of divination. That's the opposite of love! Love is generous, and often unemotional. Sometimes love is kind, and benevolent. Showing us in abundance, what we can and could do with our lives. Like the saying goes, "you don't know what you've got until it's gone." That's the Bible. That's Adam and Eve, the apple for which the taste was mightier than the pleasure. Did you ever do the same thing twice? Three times? How did you feel, bored? Meaningless? Like your life needed direction? The most difficult decisions to make in life are the ones you have to make twice. ASIAN GORL is always there for you, even when you least expect it. She's there and there's nothing you can do about it but cry on your soapbox. That's love! That's unconditional love, responsible love. Love with a purpose! It's... kintsugi!
